t of the colonial government, the social reception of Hollywood cinema, and Japanese settlers’ film culture. Filling a significant void in Asian film history, Eclipsed Cinema greatly expands the critical and historical scopes of early cinema and Korean and Japanese film histories, as well as modern Asian culture, and colonial and postcolonial studies.Key featuresExamines colonial Korean cinema at the critical junctures of Korean, Japanese and colonial cinemasIntroduces a conceptual re-figuration of colonial cinema and a new historiographical method Explores historical figures, issues and stories of colonial Korean cinema that have not yet been discussed  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMotion pictureszKoreaxHistory. 0aMotion pictures, JapanesexHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictures, KoreanxHistory and criticism. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311078140340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781474421812zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474421812423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474421812/original  a978-3-11-078140-3  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK